<subsection xml:id="subsec-negative-indices" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Negative indices</title>
    <p>
        Negative indices are used to represent the reciprocal of a number raised to a positive exponent. 
        When a base is raised to a negative exponent, it indicates that the base should be taken as the reciprocal and then raised to the absolute value of the exponent.
    </p>
    <p>
        For example, if we have a base <m>a</m> and a negative exponent <m>-n</m>, it can be expressed as:
        <m>a^{-n} = \frac{1}{a^n}</m>.
        This means that instead of multiplying <m>a</m> by itself <m>n</m> times, we take the reciprocal of <m>a^n</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        Negative indices are particularly useful in simplifying expressions and solving equations involving powers. 
        They allow us to express division in terms of multiplication, making calculations more straightforward.
    </p>
